    nextMove: "Fix Monday with shaping, not apologies: (1) immediate — client-side rate limiting on the agent's CRM client (respect their published limits with headroom), exponential backoff that actually backs off on 429s, and the briefing fan-out batched and staggered (the 8am thundering herd becomes a 5–8am rolling window; briefings are 079's async jobs — nobody needs theirs at 8:00:00); (2) cheap wins — cache the shared reads (the same account hierarchies fetched 400 times), and batch the per-seller queries the CRM API supports natively (200 calls collapses to ~20); (3) the class fix — a consumption contract per integrated system: published quota the agent fleet stays under, backpressure semantics honored, identified traffic (040's per-agent identities double as load attribution — the CRM team fire walled ONE service account because that's all they could see), and off-peak scheduling as the default for bulk work; (4) load review joins the ship gate — any capability multiplying calls to enterprise systems gets a projected-load line in its 045 checklist (calls × users × time-concentration), reviewed with the target system's owner BEFORE ship; (5) repair the relationship structurally — the CRM team gets a dashboard of agent consumption by workload and a named contact, converting them from firewall-wielders to capacity partners (049's gateway logic: visibility is what replaces walls).",
    metric: "Agent-attributed load on shared systems vs contracted quota (per system, per workload — visible to BOTH teams), and peak-concentration ratio (the 8am spike flattened into the rolling window); plus time-to-detection for the next runaway — the CRM team paged you before their users noticed, or the class fix didn't take.",
    owner: "The agent platform team owns client discipline (limits, backoff, caching) and the load-review gate; each target system's owner co-signs their consumption contract and gets the attribution dashboard; you own converting the blame thread into the contract meeting.",
    falsifier: "If load analysis shows the CRM instance was already at 90% capacity from organic growth and the agent's 8x was the straw, not the stampede — then the agent is the visible scapegoat for an under-provisioned system, the consumption contract still helps, but the honest finding routes to CRM capacity planning, and letting the agent fleet absorb the blame buys one quiet quarter before the sales floor throttles again without any agent involved.",
