  modelAnswer:
    "Start with the physics the feature ship ignored: agents are demand multipliers. A human seller checks a few accounts over a morning; an agent pre-analyzes the whole portfolio at 8am sharp, and 400 agents do it simultaneously — the integration was designed for one polite user and deployed as a synchronized stampede. The CRM team's firewall is crude, but read it correctly: it's the only control they had, because the fleet gave them nothing better — no quota to hold you to, no backpressure you honored, no attribution beyond one service account to block.\n\nMonday's fix is shaping: client-side rate limiting under their published ceiling, backoff that genuinely backs off on 429s (retrying into throttle signals is how 8x became a blame thread), and the fan-out redesigned — briefings are async jobs (079 built the runner); stagger them across a 5–8am rolling window and nobody notices except the CRM's load graph. Then the cheap wins that make the number collapse: cache the shared reads (400 briefings fetching the same account hierarchy is a cache with extra steps), and use the CRM's native batch endpoints (200 calls per seller becomes 20).\n\nThe class fix is citizenship as architecture. Per integrated system: a consumption contract — quota with headroom, honored backpressure, off-peak defaults for bulk work, and attributed traffic (040's per-agent identities mean the CRM team can see WHICH workload is hot instead of firewalling the whole fleet). And the gate: any capability that multiplies calls to shared systems ships with a projected-load line — calls × users × time-concentration — reviewed with the target system's owner first (045's checklist grows a row; the 8am spike was predictable arithmetic nobody ran). Give the CRM team the dashboard and a named contact: systems owners who can SEE agent load become capacity partners; the ones who can't build firewalls, correctly. And hold the falsifier: if their instance was already at 90% from organic growth, the agent was the straw wearing a stampede costume — the contract still ships, but the capacity finding goes where it belongs, or the sales floor throttles again next quarter with no agent to blame.",
