  modelAnswer:
    "Translate the CFO's sentence before architecting it: 'one AI layer' is an experience requirement — ask group-level questions, get group-level answers. The integrator heard a topology requirement — one tenant — and those differ by about eighteen months of migration hell and one JV lawsuit. The tenant boundaries here aren't IT territorialism: the JV wall is a contract with a co-owner, the divesting entity needs clean severance next year, and acquisition isolation is what makes M&A reversible. The boundaries ARE the business structure. Centralizing through them doesn't simplify the structure; it laminates legal risk into an index.\n\nSo decompose by workload. The CFO's actual vision is a handful of group-reach queries — consolidated vendor spend, group contract search — sitting on top of a fleet that's overwhelmingly subsidiary-local (HR agents, support agents, ops agents that never needed to see across the wall, and shouldn't — 046's classification instinct, applied to tenancy). Build the group reach as federation: a group-level agent that fans queries to per-tenant indexes, merging results through 040's intersection — the asking user's group-role determines which tenants answer, each subsidiary's data stays home under its own controls, and the audit story writes itself. Where the platform's cross-tenant support lags (020's gap, three quarters out), the interim is honest ugliness: per-tenant agents behind a thin aggregation layer — worse UX, fully detachable, and it converts into the real federation when GA lands instead of fighting it.\n\nEncode the business structure as architecture, not policy: the JV's exclusion is a connector that doesn't exist (policies get exceptions; absent connectors don't), and the divesting entity's every group-layer touchpoint is inventoried detachable-by-design — 046's flow map, repurposed as a divestiture asset that will make next year's separation a checklist instead of a crisis. Sequence by stated value: vendor spend first (finance permissions are the cleanest), contract search second (permission-heavy — 012's lessons apply at group scale), the long tail never. And convert the subsidiary IT guards from enemies to enforcement: federation makes their sovereignty the design's foundation, which is why they'll defend it (054's authorship mechanism, at holding-company scale). The falsifier stays open — if workload analysis reveals the group truly operates as one business, consolidation of the wholly-owned entities becomes honest; but even then, the JV and the divestiture never merge, which means the integrator's 'everything' was always the wrong word.",
